def: Having no chain; not restrained or fettered. "The chainlessmind." Byron.
3d pers. sing. pres. of Lie, to recline, for lieth. Chaucer.
One who receives relief for a night in a parish to which hedoes not belong; a vagrant.
The acquisition of the title or right to property by theuninterrupted possession of it for a certain term prescribed by law;-- the same as prescription in common law.

The name of a group of minerals characterized by highly perfectcleavage, so that they readily separate into very thin leaves, moreor less elastic. They differ widely in composition, and vary in colorfrom pale brown or yellow to green or black. The transparent formsare used in lanterns, the doors of stoves, etc., being popularlycalled isinglass. Formerly called also cat-silver, and glimmer.
To deprive of silver; as, to desilver lead.
A son's or daughter's child; a child in the second degree ofdescent.
Pertaining to, or like, a flock.For this gregal conformity there is an excuse. W. S. Mayo.
The quality or state of being pretty; -- used sometimes in adisparaging sense.A style . . . without sententious pretension or antitheticalprettiness. Jeffrey.
